  "prompt": "In what grade do American students learn topics like integral, derivatives, organic chemistry, and waves in detail?",
  "response": "In the American education system, topics such as integrals and derivatives are typically introduced in high school, most commonly in Advanced Placement (AP) Calculus courses, which are usually taken in 11th or 12th grade (junior or senior year). \n\nOrganic chemistry is generally taught in college-level courses, though students may get a brief introduction to some organic chemistry concepts in high school AP Chemistry, also typically taken in 11th or 12th grade.\n\nThe study of waves (including sound and light waves) is usually covered in high school physics classes, which can be taken anywhere from 9th to 12th grade depending on the school curriculum and the student's course choices. More detailed study of waves, including advanced concepts from physical wave theory, might be reserved for college-level physics courses.\n\nOverall, high school students typically get their first exposure to these topics in their junior or senior year, but more in-depth and specialized study generally occurs at the college level.",
